courts vs. arbitration. Arbitration is usually preferable for cross-border deals; courts for domestic.\n\n# 3. Battle of forms\n\nWhen buyers issue an RFQ pack containing both an MSA and standalone T&Cs:\n\n- The **T&Cs almost always state they prevail over any other document.** That clause is often in the GTCs themselves and is the first place to look.\n- The MSA may contain a contradictory order-of-precedence clause (MSA prevails). Flag both clauses for the negotiation table.\n- Pricing schedules, SLAs, and annexes often carry their own clauses purporting to override the MSA. Map the precedence stack on a single page before negotiating.\n- The bidder's accepted position should normally be: **bid response wording > redlined MSA > buyer's GTCs**, with any annexes ranking below the MSA. If the buyer refuses to flip the precedence, the bidder is effectively bidding on the T&Cs alone — price accordingly.\n\n# 4. Procurement-specific risk areas\n\nThese show up in procurement-led bids more than in standalone deals:\n\n- **Audit rights extending to subsidiaries and sub-suppliers** — supplier may not be able to grant these. Limit to the supplier and named principal sub-suppliers.\n- **ESG attestation requirements** that demand a certifying signature at director level — confirm the bidder can attest accurately, particularly around Scope 3 emissions and SBTi targets. Negative attestations on disclosed non-compliance are usually safer than over-claiming.\n- **Data Processing Annex by reference** — never accept \"as updated by the controller from time to time\" wording. The DPA must be fixed at a known version with negotiated change procedure.\n- **Cyber-security minima** baked into the compliance annex (Cyber Essentials Plus, MFA, encryption, pen-testing, incident-notification windows) — these are often achievable but the timelines and audit rights need scoping.\n- **Strategic stock holding** — confirm the supplier is being compensated for stock-holding cost, including capit